# Note: Adjust the range accordingly if you decide to extend this to more days
date_lookup = spark.sql("""
SELECT explode(sequence(
    to_timestamp('2024-01-01 00:00:00'), 
    to_timestamp('2024-01-01 23:59:59'), 
    interval 1 second
)) as timestamp
""")
date_lookup=date_lookup.withColumnRenamed("timestamp","date and time")
# Show some of the DataFrame to verify - displaying all would be impractical
display(date_lookup)
date_lookup.count()  # Should show 86,400 for a single day

from pyspark.sql import SparkSession
from pyspark.sql import functions as F

# Create a Spark session
spark = SparkSession.builder.appName("Jan2023Dates").getOrCreate()

# Define the start and end dates for January 2024
start_date = "2023-01-01"
end_date = "2023-01-31"

# Create a DataFrame with a single row
single_row_df = spark.createDataFrame([(1,)], ["dummy"])

# Use explode to generate dates for January 2024
jan_2023_dates_df = single_row_df.selectExpr(f"explode(sequence(to_date('{start_date}'), to_date('{end_date}'), interval 1 day)) AS Date")

# Show the DataFrame
jan_2023_dates_df.show(truncate=False)
